    "narrative": "For our April 29th slate, the lineup is anchored by **Corbin Carroll** (74.01) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92), who represent our strongest offensive upside. **Corbin Carroll** remains a priority start, with his profile bolstered by an favorable matchup against Sproat and a solid xwOBA (0.372). **Vinnie Pasquantino** benefits from a strong park factor (+10%) and an excellent platoon setup against the right-handed Luis Severino. Similarly, **Tyler Soderstrom** (72.72) and **Josh Naylor** (71.58) provide elite efficiency; **Tyler Soderstrom** specifically thrives in this park environment against Wacha, and **Josh Naylor** capitalizes on a high SP_xERA for the opposing arm, making these four the bedrock of today\u2019s pursuit of RBI and HR production.\n\nOur deepest efficiency gains today are driven by opportunistic matchups. **Kyle Karros** (63.06) is a surprising riser, as a 5.40 SP_xERA for Williamson and a +5% wind factor inflate his score well above his base projection. While we are prioritizing stolen bases, **Trevor Story** (61.48) earns his spot today through a specific BvP edge (+8%) against Lauer, suggesting we can stomach a less-than-ideal park factor. Conversely, **Jose Caballero** remains a high-risk play (41.62) due to his spot in the order and a tough matchup against Eovaldi; he remains in the lineup purely to chase the scarcity of SB, though he is on the precipice of being benched if he fails to secure early bag opportunities.\n\nThe most difficult decision at the margins involved **Alex Freeland** (47.61), who fell just shy of the threshold to displace our lower-tier starters. While **Alex Freeland** offers switch-hitting versatility, his placement in the #9 hole dragged his efficiency score down enough to favor **Mickey Moniak** or the remaining core. We also weighed **Austin Riley** (42.36) against elite opposition; however, the significant difficulty posed by Tarik Skubal (2.71 xERA) made him a clear bench candidate to preserve our game caps. We remain cautious regarding **Vinnie Pasquantino**, **Brice Turang**, **James Wood**, and **Tyler Soderstrom**, all of whom are currently projected based on assumed lineup positions; any downward shift in their respective batting orders prior to first pitch will necessitate a recalibration of their daily efficiency scores.",
